  <static seed="1284" source="Contrib/PCC/BasicAlgebra/RationalExpressionAlgebraSkills/simplifyRationalExpressions130.pg">
    <statement><p>Simplify the following expression, and if applicable, write the restricted domain on the simplified expression.</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{{\frac{x^{2}-8x+15}{6x-x^{2}-9}}=}</m> <fillin characters="19" name="AnSwEr0001"/></p>
</statement>
    <answer>
      <p>
        <m>-\frac{x-5}{x-3}, \left(-\infty ,\infty \right)</m>
      </p>
    </answer>
    <solution><p>To simplify the expression, we first factor both the numerator and denominator, and then cross out common factors.</p>
<p>If a polynomial is not in order, we order it by the variable<rsq/>s degrees.</p>
<p>If the leading coefficient is negative, we factor out <m>-1</m>.</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{\begin{aligned}
   {\frac{x^{2}-8x+15}{6x-x^{2}-9}} \amp = \frac{{\left(x-5\right)\mathopen{}\left(x-3\right)}}{{-x^{2}+6x-9}} \\
                     \amp = \frac{{\left(x-5\right)\mathopen{}\left(x-3\right)}}{{-\left(x^{2}-6x+9\right)}} \\
                     \amp = \frac{{\left(x-5\right)\mathopen{}\left(x-3\right)}}{{-\left(x-3\right)^{2}}} \\
                     \amp = {-\frac{x-5}{x-3}, \left(-\infty ,\infty \right)}
\end{aligned}
    }</m></p>
<p>Since the factor <m>x - 3</m> was crossed out, the domain condition lost during the simplification is <m>x \ne 3</m>.</p>
</solution>
